title: Socio-Economic Conditions and Public Health Outcomes in Idaho
author: Author A. B.
summary: This study investigates how socio-economic conditions in Idaho affect public health indicators such as chronic disease rates, mortality, and access to care. Data from state-level health departments and national surveys were utilized to assess disparities.

statistical_analysis.findings: The study found that counties in Idaho with higher poverty rates and lower educational attainment were significantly more likely to report negative health outcomes. These disparities were moderated by local healthcare access and urbanicity.

policy_implication: Policymakers in Idaho are encouraged to target social determinants of health by improving access to education, employment, and healthcare. Investing in public health infrastructure could help reduce disparities and improve statewide health outcomes.

policy_implication: Policymakers in New Hampshire are encouraged to target social determinants of health by improving access to education, employment, and healthcare. Investing in public health infrastructure could help reduce disparities and improve statewide health outcomes.
references: New Hampshire State Health Department Reports, 2019
